article.description:
DeMya Walker scored a layup with .8
seconds left to lift the Sacramento Monarchs to a 66-64 victory over
the San Antonio Silver Stars on Thursday night.
article.headline: Stars rally in final three minutes to tie
article.linkText: Walker's layup give Monarchs last say vs. Stars
article.story:
SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- DeMya Walker scored just five points,
but her layup with .8 seconds left gave the Monarchs a 66-64 win
over the struggling San Antonio Silver Stars on Thursday night.

Walker got the inbounds pass near the top of the key and drove
past defender Nevriye Yilmaz for a left-handed layup.

"There was not a lot of time left, I just wanted to attack the
basket," Walker said.

LaToya Thomas, who scored a game-high 24 points for the Silver
Stars, made a 3-pointer with 3.8 seconds left to tie the game at
64.

"The shot for LaToya was something we called in the timeout and
it worked," San Antonio coach Shell Dailey said. "All we needed
after that was a stop and we didn't get it."

Tangela Smith had 16 points and Yolanda Griffith added 15 for
Sacramento. It was the third straight victory and fourth in five
games for the Monarchs (14-13), who pulled ahead of idle Phoenix
for fourth place in the Western Conference.

The losses continue to pile up for the last-place Silver Stars
(6-22), who have dropped eight straight games and 13 of 14 overall.

The Monarchs begin five consecutive road games in 13 days with a
rematch against San Antonio on Saturday.

"The road trip will be very important for us," Griffith said.
"It will determine if we make the playoffs or not."

After squandering an 11-point lead, the Monarchs scored nine
straight points. But the Stars rallied in the final three minutes
to tie the game.

Semeka Randall added 16 points and seven rebounds for San
Antonio.

Edna Campbell had 10 points for the Monarchs, who made 22-of-26
free throws and led 28-23 at halftime.

Six Olympians, including five-time gold medal winner Eric
Heiden, honored gold-medalist Griffith before the game.
